This index is very volatile, so I think it's hard to be very certain about any particular bin. Lately, it routinely moves over points or more in a couple weeks, which would be enough to put it in a higher or lower bin. The higher bin would be more difficult to reach at this point, with only 2 weeks left, but with natural gas prices hitting new highs, I don't rule that out, although the index is pretty uncoupled from natural gas prices. But I'm a lot less certain than the crowd is about how this question will resolve. (And I'm sure I'll end up with a lower score for it in the end.)

3 weeks left in the forecast period. I do think the overall trend is probably slightly downward, so I'm weighting bin 2 higher than bin 4. Granted, the index hasn't been below 800 since Sept 3, 2021, but it could well fall now, as natural gas prices are falling. Because of the volatility in this index, I'm weighing bin 3 far lower than the crowd. The index moved up ~86 points from July 29 to Aug 5, so it could easily move ~100 pts in the coming 3 weeks. But the crowd will probably end up right....

Upward movement for the second week in a row, with the index now at 897.76. 8 more weeks to go in the forecast. In the past couple years, the biggest drop in 8 weeks has been just over 300. So I don't completely rule out <600. The biggest gain in 8 weeks has been almost 500, so I don't completely rule out the last bin, either. But unless there's a big shock, the highest bin doesn't look likely. I don't understand why the index isn't falling gently, esp as natural gas prices continue to fall. Maybe this reflects a peak in fertilizer usage? So, it's not clear to me which way this will go. Given the volatility in the index, I also can't share the crowd's level of certainty about bin 3.

Uncertainty about Russian intent has vanished and the invasion is now impacting many sectors worldwide. Signals (listed below) indicate rising fertilizer prices (overall world food prices) and related energy required mine/make them are still trending up two weeks after the invasion. Despite the U.S. attempts to sanction Russia and seek energy from other places, even Venezuela and Iran, the steady increases in price will likely continue for several weeks until offset measures are in place. Even then, uncertainty abounds as to the effect the measures will reduce prices to pre-invasion levels.
Adjusting for predicted higher gas prices

BASE RATE Fertilizer ingredients are all higher than the 2008 market highs and climbing. Price of natural gas at record highs. Tariff percentages impact roughly 9.5% of increases, potentially more in the future. Russian actions impacting Ukraine are unknown and likely impacting prices (hedging). BIAS Inside look (domestic) first appears important because we care most about our own economy. Closer examination we see that global market signaling plays a more substantial role (i.e. potash, natural gas, etc.) UNCERTAINTY The US is the third-largest producer of fertilizer yet farming efficiencies and desire to reduce chemicals in farming (organics) have reduced fertilizer demand since 1961. The US at 25% of world consumption in 1961 to just 10% in 2018 and if the trend continues shows potentially 5% by 2038. This is the linkage between supply and demand means the US must pay the global prices for raw materials to make fertilizer, even though it is not its largest consumer of fertilizer. Also, COVID interrupted supply chains and production but the rebound from COVID as conditions return to the new normal are unknown. And, Russia, home of Uralkali and EuroChem potash mines, face possible economic sanctions if it invades Ukraine. Finally, hurricane IDA knocked out the supply from CF Industries, the largest fertilizer producer in the world. Plus CF Industries has been forced to close fertilizer plants in the UK due to soaring natural gas prices. Will CF industries return to production or fold? SIGNAL Supply— Ingredients: Global rates for major nutrients used in the production of fertilizer: nitrogen (anhydrous ammonia, urea, or liquid nitrogen), phosphorus (diammonium phosphate – DAP and mono ammonium phosphate – MAP), and potassium (potash). Energy: The price of natural gas skyrockets and increases the cost of production, as in the case of synthesizing ammonia, U.S. producers can no longer compete with other global producers who may have a lower cost of production. Tariffs: New antidumping and countervailing duty tariffs on urea ammonium nitrate (UAN) solutions, a prime material in nitrogen fertilizer, are expected to raise the prices for both domestically produced and imported nitrogen fertilizers by the same percentage as the tariffs, which have been preliminarily Producers: What is the fate of CF Industries (largest fertilizer producer in the world)? Demand— Two-thirds of global fertilizer demand is driven primarily by six crops: corn represents about 16%, wheat about 15%, rice represents about 14%, vegetables at 9%, fruits at 7%, and soybeans at 5%. SCOPE Now through the week of 26 August 2022. Less than 600; between 600 and 800 inclusive; more than 800 but less than 1,000; between 1,000 and 1,200 inclusive; more than 1,200. Historic data collected/analyzed spanning from 1961 to the present.

Its too volatile to say specifically where this is going. The overall trend is decreasing, despite a recent uptick. With alternative growing methods gaining popularity and decreasing demand of fertilizer, I'm tempted to forecast 6-8, but thats hopeful. 8-1 stays in current range, which is what i expect for this growing season.

Although a number of factors are driving up the price of fertilizer, I don't believe that the market would support a low value but it seems unlikely that it could be driven higher than 1200. Based on the importance of fertilizer to the agricultural industry, I believe that government offsets or subsidies would be enacted to prevent hyperinflation.

oil price and spring demand in question

Feb 3, 2022 Reuters Agriculture heavyweights like Bayer AG, in developing farm products that use living things like microbes and seaweed to nourish crops and lessen the need for synthetic fertilizer. Tech companies are attracting funding as commercial nitrogen and potash fertilizers are in tight supply. https://www.reuters.com/markets/commodities/fertilizer-shortage-may-lead-spring-scramble-north-americas-farms-2021-11-24 Microbial fertilizers may help in the distant future to fill in the gap but likely not to have significant impact by August 2022. Therefore, adjusting my probabilities slightly only.

August is the end of growing season and before the fertilization of soil after the harvest. Demand is likely to be very low in August and with whatever political solutions are emplaced, the price will be under control.

North American fertilizer prices peaked around 1,100 towards the end of last year, late purchasing in the northern hemisphere will see prices exceed this level, but buyers will forgo planting with the increased economic risk associated with prices over 1,200.
